For if we look into the Sehoolmen they place the whole argument of ecclesiastical fasting in a difference and choice of meats, not in abstinence and moderation. Hence Hales, part. 4. quaest. 28. memb. 3. art. 2, contends, that we are to abstain in the time of fasting not so much from quantity as from quality .- for he asserts, that during the time of fasting, it is a greater sin to eat a little flesh, than to devour much fish. And Durandus, lib. 4. dist. 7. quaest 4, writes, ΤΙιαιι α Popislz fast is not broken by one meal, however great, pro- vided they abstaz'nfrom tlte meats prolzibited, i. e. from flesh, egge, and milk. Hence it comes to pass that the Papists feel no scruple to taste wine or fish, however delicate, dur- ing Lent, or figs, dates, and almost all other articles which are accounted delicacies, provided they religiously take care not to eat flesh. No wonder fasts are so pleasing to them to whom it is holiness to fast in this manner.
